{"id":"project-LICHEN-r5r7","title":"senml: decode buffer overflow check may reject valid input","description":"File: rust/lichen-senml/src/cbor.rs
Lines: 440-442

The decode function checks:
```rust
if n_recs > buf.len() {
    return Err(CborError::InvalidInput);
}
```

This returns InvalidInput when the buffer is too small, but InvalidInput implies the CBOR data is malformed. The actual issue is that the caller provided an insufficient buffer.

This causes two problems:
1. Wrong error type - should be BufferTooSmall to match the encoder's behavior
2. Caller cannot distinguish 'bad CBOR' from 'need bigger buffer'

Impact: Callers cannot handle buffer-too-small case correctly; error handling is inconsistent with encode().

Fix:
```rust
if n_recs > buf.len() {
    return Err(CborError::BufferTooSmall(
        BufferTooSmall::new(n_recs, buf.len())
    ));
}
